    <title>Combined summary - eltoo: A Simplified update Mechanism for Lightning and Off-Chain Contracts</title>
    <updated>2023-05-25T00:13:08.159681+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2018-June/001311.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email conversations revolve around the Lightning Network and proposed improvements to the penalty-based invalidation system. One of the proposed improvements is the eltoo mechanism, which involves off-chain transactions with different branches and encumbrances. The update transaction script has two branches, and settlement transactions can carry contracts but are affected by the CSV-encumbrance. There are discussions about potential attacks on the Lightning Network, including DoS against Eltoo settlements and HTLC theft, as well as possible mitigations such as reducing Replace-By-Fee grouping depth or delaying propagation proportional to tx weight. It is emphasized that setting the HTLC time-out increment at least to S+C is important to prevent closing all channels on the route if a transaction time-out occurs. Another proposed improvement is the Decker-Russell-Osuntokun channels as a potential replacement for LN-penalty channels. However, they have some downsides, including less control over fees that a misbehaving node may get punished with. ZmnSCPxj proposes an adaptive approach where a second update transaction is added at around 90% of the available range to increase the number of possible updates. Christian Decker suggests an alternative approach involving a funding address that is a multisig owned by both parties, followed by a simpler ratchet mechanism. The email conversations also discuss some clarifications and naming conventions regarding the setup transaction and its output, as well as the possibility of having a second output (change) in the transaction. ZmnSCPxj proposes introducing a new feature to the Lightning Network called Decker-Russell-Osuntokun as a back-compatible extension, creating a mixed network where payers could route through either Poon-Dryja channels or a combination of Poon-Dryja and Decker-Russell-Osuntokun channels. Overall, the email conversations provide insights into various aspects of the Lightning Network, including proposed improvements and potential attacks and mitigations.</summary>
